Name: Auschwitz concentration camp
Description: This, the largest Nazi concentration and extermination camp, was established in June 1940. It was joined in 1941 by Auschwitz II (Birkenau) and in 1942 by Auschwitz III (Monowitz).  Between 2.1 and 2.5 million died in the seven gas chambers of the complex.

Name: Bendsburg concentration camp
Description: Camp located near the town of the same name in eastern Upper Silesia.

Name: Belzec concentration camp
Description: Created to to murder the Jews of the Lublin district of Poland, Belzec was the first of the three so called "Aktion Reinhard" extermination camps. Belzec began operation in March 1942, and by December, when operations ceased, the total number of deaths had reached about 434,000.

Name: Bergen-Belsen concentration camp
Description: Established in the spring of 1943 and initially intended as a transit camp, it soon was integrated into the concentration camp network.  Its population swelled late in the war as inmates from other camps further east were moved into it--from around 15,000 in late 1944 to 41,250 in March 1945.

Name: Birkenheim
Description: Part of Organisation Schmelt camps network, this was a labor camp located in Lower Silesia.

Name: Buchenwald concentration camp
Description: Established in July 1937 near the city of Weimar for prisoners from central Germany, who were put to work making bricks at a nearby clay pit.  Around 9000 were normally housed there, but the population reached around 48,000 by April 1945.

Name: Börgermoor concentration camp
Description: Initially created in 1933 as a camp for political prisoners and other criminals, later used to imprison resistance fighters and other military prisoners. In 1944 it became a subcamp of Neuengamme; in April 1945 most prisoners were sent on a forced death march to Aschendorfermoor.

Name: Częstochowa concentration camp
Description: Established in April 1941, it was largely liquidated in September-October 1942 and the survivors sent to the Treblinka concentration camp.  A "Small Ghetto" of around 5000 remained of the strongest and best-educated, but these were dispersed or liquidated as well by July 1943.

Name: Dachau concentration camp
Description: The first concentration camp opened in Germany (March 1933), located on the grounds of an abandoned munitions factory near the medieval town of Dachau, about 16 km (10 miles) northwest of Munich. In total, over 200,000 prisoners from more than 30 countries were housed in Dachau.

Name: Mittelbau-Dora concentration camp
Description: This camp produced V-2 rockets near Nordhausen in Thuringia from August 1943 to April 1945.

Name: Drancy concentration camp
Description: The camp was opened after a roundup of in Paris Jews in August, 1941, in which over 4000 Jews were arrested.  Drancy was under the control of the French police until July 3, 1943 when Nazi Germany took day-to-day control as part of the major stepping up at all facilities for the mass exterminations.

Name: Flossenbürg concentration camp
Description: Concentration camp built in May 1938 by the SS in the Oberpfalz region of Bavaria. Between 1938 and liberation in April 1945, more than 96,000 prisoners passed through Flossenbürg. About 28,000 died there.

Name: Fort de Romainville concentration camp
Description: Germans claim it in October 1940 and first prisoners are interned in November 1940. Most of the prisoners of this camp were from the Resistance. They would be shot in the lager or sent away to Germany.

Name: Gogolin concentration camp
Description: This was a forced labor camp located in Upper Silesia, established in 1940 for Jews from the surrounding area, and remained in operation for several years.

Name: Gross Masselwitz concentration camp
Description: Originally established as a labor camp in 1939 for displaced Poles seeking work near Breslau, Silesia.

Name: Gross-Rosen concentration camp
Description: Established in Silesia in 1940 as a satellite camp to Sachsenhausen, it became an independent camp in 1941. Work centered on a huge stone quarry and many sub-camps were established (reaching 60 in 1944).

Name: Gurs concentration camp
Description: This camp in southwestern France near the Spanish border received German Jews from Baden in October 1942.  The camp was largely emptied in August 1942 when its inmates were sent east to other camps; most were sent to Auschwitz.

Name: Haidari concentration camp
Description: Located in the Haidari suburb of Athens, it operated from September 1943 until September 1944 as the largest concentration camp in Greece.

Name: Herzogenburg concentration camp
Description: Forced labor camp primarily populated by non-Jews, which held French, Greek, Polish, Lithuanian, and Bulgarian prisoners.

Name: Janinagrube concentration camp
Description: This camp, located around 11 miles from Auschwitz, was a coal mining operation.  Initially worked by British POWS, they were replaced by Jews from Auschwitz in September 1943.

Name: Janowska concentration camp
Description: This labor, transit and concentration camp was established in occupied Poland in September 1941 on the outskirts of Lvov (today in Ukraine).  It was liquidated in November 1943.

Name: Karviná concentration camp
Description: Currently a city in the Moravian-Silesian Region of the Czech Republic, on the Olza River.  It was annexed by Poland in October 1938 and was administered by Germany as part of occupied Poland during World War II.

Name: Kiełbasin concentration camp
Description: This transit camp was involved in the liquidation of the Hrodna (or Grodno) Ghetto in Belarus in the winter of 1942-43.

Name: Klettendorf concentration camp
Description: This forced labor camp stood in Breslau (now Wroclaw), Silesia and was first mentioned in August 1940.  Various companies in the region used its inmates in various industries (steel, brick, carpentry, furniture, wool) and on Autobahn projects.  The camp closed by July 1944.

Name: Płaszów concentration camp
Description: A concentration camp located near Krakow, Poland.

Name: Le Vernet concentration camp
Description: Originally a French military camp and depot, in 1942 it became a transit camp for detained Jews. In June 1944 the last internees were evacuated and deported to the Dachau concentration camp in the "Ghost Train."

Name: Les Avants
Description: Internment camp for political refugees seeking asylum, maintained by the Swiss government.

Name: Les Milles concentration camp
alt_name: Camp des Milles;Internierungs- und Deportationslager Les Milles;Internierungslager Les Milles
Description: Between 1941 and 1942 Le Camp des Milles was used as a transit camp for Jews, mainly men. About 2,000 of the inmates were shipped off to the Drancy internment camp on the way to Auschwitz.

Name: Limoges
Description: A city and commune in France, the préfecture of the Haute-Vienne département, and the administrative capital of the Limousin région.

Name: Majdanek concentration camp
Description: This camp in the Polish city of Lubin operated from 1941 to 1944.  It contained Jewish prisoners from Slovakia, the Czech lands, Austria, Germany, France and Holland. From mid-1942 until mid-1943 most of the Jews sent to the camp were from the Lublin region and the ghettos of Warsaw and Bialystok.

Name: Mauthausen concentration camp
Description: Opened in August 1938 to provide labor for a granite quarry, in January 1941 it became a grade III camp for "Incorrigible Political Enemies of the Reich."

Name: Struthof concentration camp
Description: Operational from May 1941 to September 1944, Natzweiler-Struthof was a German concentration and extermination camp located in the Vosges Mountains close to the Alsatian village of Natzwiller, near the city of Strasbourg.  It was the only Nazi concentration camp established on French territory.

Name: Neustadt
Description: Forced labor camp for non-Jewish deportees, located on the Black Sea in West Prussia.

Name: Nováky concentration camp
Description: Novaky was liberated in August 1944 during the Slovak National Uprising.

Name: Noé concentration camp
Description: Located 25 miles south of Toulouse.

Name: Esterwegen concentration camp
Description: Located near the Dutch border, this SS-run camp largely contained political prisoners.

Name: Pithiviers concentration camp
Description: Located near Orléans in the Loiret region of France.

Name: Fort VII concentration camp
Description: Originally build as a Prussian fort on the outskirts of Posen (Poznan), this compound was the first on Polish soil to be designated as a concentration camp following the fall of Poland in September 1939.

Name: Pravieniškės concentration camp
Description: The prison in this town was founded in 1863 by the Tsarist regime following a Lituanian uprising.  It became a Nazi concentration camp before becoming a Soviet labor camp.

Name: Pustków concentration camp
Description: The first prisoners arrived in 1940, mostly Polish Jews. In 1941 the German forces built a second camp for Russian prisoners of war, and in 1942 built a third camp for Polish workers.  In early August 1944 the three camps were totally evacuated and destroyed, with the survivors moved to other camps.

Name: Ravensbrück concentration camp
Description: Concentration camp for female prisoners. By 1944, Ravensbrück and its 34 subcamps had a prisoner population of more than 80,000. Tens of thousands perished there from malnutrition, disease, shootings, phenol injections to the heart, and medical experiments. Six thousand died in its gas chambers.

Name: Riesenburg
Description: This town, known as Prabuty in Polish, was called Riesenburg.  It is situated in northern Poland, about forty miles south of the Gulf of Danzig.

Name: Rivesaltes concentration camp
alt_name: Camp d'hébergement de Rivesaltes;Camp de Rivesaltes;Camp Joffre
Description: In 1942, under German pressure, the camp became a "Centre national de rassemblement des Israélites" - a "sorting centre" for Jews who were then sent on to the death camps such as Auschwitz, via Drancy. Two thousand five hundred and fifty one Jews are recorded as having been deported from Rivesaltes.

Name: Royallieu concentration camp
Description: This detention camp operated from June 1941 to August 1944 and was located in the French commune of Compiègne. Prisoners included French Communists, Resistance fighters, and Soviet citizens as well as Jews.

Name: Roznow
Description: This work camp was located in southeastern Poland.

Name: Reichshof concentration camp
Description: Slave labor camp serving an airplane engine factory in the nearby village of Lysia Gora. On the eve of the German occupation, there were some 14,000 Jews in Rzeszów, the vast majority of whom did not survive.

Name: Sachsenhausen concentration camp
Description: Concentration camp opened in 1936. Prisoners were employed in various branches of armament manufacture, especially airplane and tank engines. Some 200,000 prisoners passed through the camp. The exact number of those who perished is unknown.

Name: Septfonds concentration camp
Description: This camp in southwestern France was a collecting point for many Jews who were later sent east to death camps such as Auschwitz.

Name: Schaulen concentration camp
Description: Following the German occupation of this Lithuanian city in June 1941 (which was one-quarter Jewish in 1939), 1000 Jews were shot within the first weeks, after which two ghetto areas were established (in the Kaukas and Traku areas). Only 500 area Jews survived until liberation in 1944.

Name: Skarżysko-Kamienna concentration camp
Description: This forced labor camp produced munitions.

Name: Sobibór concentration camp
Description: This extermination camp near Lublin including Jewish Soviet POWs; up to 250,000 were gassed there.  After a successful revolt on October 14, 1943 about half of the 600 prisoners in Sobibor escaped; the camp was closed and planted with trees soon after.

Name: Starachowice concentration camp
Description: This labor camp, created in the summer for survivors of the liquidated Starachowice Ghetto, came to be known as Julag I and housed around 5000 at a time.  In the summer of 1943 the inmates were moved to a new location, known as Julag II; this final camp was liquidated in July 1944.

Name: Stutthof concentration camp
Description: Completed in September 1939, it was located in the small town of Sztutowo (German: Stutthof) in the former territory of the Free City of Danzig. Stutthof was the last camp liberated by the Allies. More than 85,000 victims died in the camp out of as many 110,000 who were sent there.

Name: Szebnie concentration camp
Description: Located near Jaslo, Krakow district, this work camp was liquidated on November 3, 1943 through mass executions of its inmates.

Name: Treblinka concentration camp
Description: The largest of the "Aktion Reinhard" camps, this extermination camp was created to murder the Jews of the Warsaw ghetto and other ghettos in central Poland. From July 1942 to October 1943, more than 800,000 Jews and several thousand Roma were killed there.

Name: Vyhne concentration camp
Description: Labor camp created by the Slovakian government in 1942 on the site of a health resort.

Name: Weidenberg
Description: No information on this camp could be found.

Name: Wejherowo
Description: Formerly Neustadt, West Prussia, this town was located near Danzig/Gdansk.

Name: Wischau
Description: Located in the modern Czech Republic.
